    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p><add>German</add> With the wish for your happiness, and that<lb/> you may declare
                yourself my friend openly as you are<lb/> in secret,</p>
            <p><persName role="author">I. Kalisch</persName>.</p>
            <p>
                <add>Hebrew</add>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <hi rend="underline">Announcement</hi>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In order that no complaint be made against me and<lb/> other rabbis
                that we objected to the <hi rend="underline">Get</hi> which was given here<lb/> in
                    <placeName>Cleveland</placeName>, and lest it be said that we transgressed the
                Edict<lb/> of the rabbis not to leave matters of divorce to gentiles, that is<lb/>
                why I publicly announce that since the one who arranged the<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Get</hi> did not understand the nature of the laws on marriage
                and<lb/> divorce, his actions and words are not to be considered, and<lb/> with
                regard to this sort of <hi rend="underline">Get</hi> there is no applicability of
                the<lb/> law about spreading false rumors [See <persName>Maharik</persName>
                §36,<lb/> and other legalists]</p>
            <p>And the following is evidence that this man had<lb/> no knowledge of the nature of
                divorce</p>
            <list type="ordered">
                <head/>
                <item n="1"> He did not know that it was necessary to ask the<lb/> man whether he
                    had not vowed to his wife not to divorce<lb/> her, in which case it is first
                    necessary to free him<lb/> from his oath, lest he be caught in the net of a
                    false<lb/> oath, as I have written in my first letter.</item>
                <item n="2">
                    <del>There was</del> The court had become invalidated</item>
                <item n="3"> Further proof is in the fact that the one who arranged<lb/> the divorce
                    had written in this magazine that he had<lb/> found no law about names of new
                    places, while,<lb/> as a matter of fact, there are piles of such laws</item>
            </list>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>If the matter had come before me, I would have<lb/> investigated very closely, and
                asked scholars<lb/> what the legal name of the place should be. This<lb/> is what
                any sensible man would do, and not<lb/> like this perverse and stupid fellow
                about<lb/> whom it is said "and it happened when<lb/> the judges judged"*, and about
                when the<lb/> sages said that he is the kind that compares<lb/> himself to
                    <persName>Elazar ben Arach</persName>, as superior<lb/> to everyone else.</p>
            <p>These are the words of</p>
            <p><persName role="author">Israel</persName> son of <persName>Simha Bunas
                    Kalisch</persName></p>
            <p>Head of Court of <placeName>Cleveland</placeName></p>
            <p>
                <date>(Ellul 1854)</date>
            </p>
            <p>* The reference is "each man did what seemed good<lb/> in his eyes"</p>
        </body>
